properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 22 at 7:28AM EDT until April 22 at 8:00AM EDT by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Greenville-Spartanburg has issued a

* Tornado Warning for...
Northwestern Cabarrus County in the Piedmont of North Carolina...
Southeastern Iredell County in the Piedmont of North Carolina...
North central Mecklenburg County in the Piedmont of North
Carolina...
Southwestern Rowan County in the Piedmont of North Carolina...

* Until 800 AM EDT.

* At 728 AM EDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing a tornado
was located 8 miles north of Huntersville, or near Davidson, moving
east at 45 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Expect damage to mobile homes, roofs, and vehicles.

* This dangerous storm will be near...
Mooresville around 730 AM EDT.
Enochville around 740 AM EDT.
Kannapolis, China Grove and Landis around 750 AM EDT.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

Please report damaging winds, hail, or flooding to the National
Weather Service by calling toll free, 1, 800, 2 6 7, 8 1 0 1, or by
posting on our Facebook page, or Tweet it using hashtag nwsgsp. Your
message should describe the event and the specific location where it
occurred.

CMAMtext: NWS: TORNADO WARNING in this area til 8:00 AM EDT. Take shelter now. Check media.
CMAMlongtext: National Weather Service: TORNADO WARNING in this area until 8:00 AM EDT. Take shelter now in a basement or an interior room on the lowest floor of a sturdy building. If you are outdoors, in a mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter and protect yourself from flying debris. Check media.

properties.headline: Severe Thunderstorm Warning issued April 22 at 7:22AM EDT until April 22 at 7:45AM EDT by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
properties.description:
At 721 AM EDT, a severe thunderstorm was located 8 miles west of
Huntersville, or 5 miles northeast of Mt Holly, moving east at 35
mph.

HAZARD...60 mph wind gusts.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Expect damage to trees and power lines.

Locations impacted include...
Huntersville, North and Northwest Charlotte, West Concord,
Cornelius, Mt Holly, Harrisburg, University City, Reedy Creek Park
and Charlotte Motor Speedway.
properties.instruction:
Remain alert for a possible tornado! Tornadoes can develop quickly
from severe thunderstorms. If you spot a tornado go at once into the
basement or small central room in a sturdy structure.

A few trees and power lines will be blown down in the warned area.
The storm will be accompanied by brief heavy rainfall, and little or
no lightning. Seek shelter inside an interior room.

Please report damaging winds, hail, or flooding to the National
Weather Service by calling toll free, 1, 800, 2 6 7, 8 1 0 1, or by
posting on our Facebook page, or Tweet it using hashtag nwsgsp. Your
message should describe the event and the specific location where it
occurred.

Move to safe harbor until hazardous weather passes. Boaters should
seek safe harbor immediately until these storms pass. If caught on
the open water, prepare for deteriorating conditions. Make sure you
and your crew are wearing properly fitted life jackets.

Frequent lightning is occurring with this storm. If caught on the
open water stay below deck if possible, keep away from ungrounded
metal objects.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 22 at 7:01AM EDT by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
properties.description:
At 701 AM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking strong thunderstorms along
a line extending from 3 miles northeast of Boomer to 9 miles
northeast of Newton to 6 miles north of Lincolnton. Movement was east
at 35 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 40 mph and pea size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor damage to outdoor objects is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Gastonia, Uptown Charlotte, Huntersville, Kannapolis, Downtown
Concord, Statesville, Newton, Lincolnton, Mocksville and
Taylorsville.
properties.instruction:
If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with these storms.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

At 629 AM EDT, Doppler radar indicated a cluster of strong
thunderstorms, capable of producing wind gusts to around 30 knots.
These thunderstorms are located near C J Davidson Wreck and extend
southeast to near Georgetown 85 Reef. These storms are moving
northeast at 20 knots.

Locations impacted include...
Ten Mile Reef, Vermillion Reef, Little River Sea Buoy, 2 C R Ledge,
Gary Ennis Reef, Winyah Bay Sea Buoy, City Of Richmond, Sherman
Wreck, Bill Perry Junior Reef, Greenville Reef, Murrells Inlet Sea
Buoy, Georgetown Nearshore Wreck, Little River Offshore Reef, Myrtle
Beach Rock, Atlantic Ledge, Inshore Hole, Springmaid Pier, Horseshoe
Area, Georgetown Reef and Paradise Reef.
properties.instruction:
Mariners can expect gusty winds to around 30 knots, locally higher
waves, and lightning strikes. Boaters should seek safe harbor
immediately until this storm passes. If caught on the open water,
prepare for deteriorating conditions. Make sure you and your crew are
wearing properly fitted life jackets.

NWSheadline: A STRONG THUNDERSTORM OVER THE WATERS

properties.areaDesc: Giles; Pulaski; Montgomery; Craig; Alleghany; Roanoke; Monroe; Eastern Greenbrier
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 22 at 6:25AM EDT by NWS Blacksburg VA
properties.description:
At 624 AM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking a strong thunderstorm over
Pearisburg, moving northeast at 40 mph.

HAZARD...Winds in excess of 40 mph.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects.

Locations impacted include...
Blacksburg...
Christiansburg...
Radford...
Alleghany...
Pulaski...
Pearisburg...
and Dublin.
properties.instruction:
If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Locally heavy rain will quickly reduce visibility and result in
ponding of water on roadways, standing water in low lying areas, and
minor flooding of creeks, streams, and areas of poor drainage.
Drivers are urged to slow down and use extra caution to avoid
hydroplaning.

NWSheadline: A strong thunderstorm will impact portions of orthwestern Roanoke and western Alleghany Counties in west central Virginia, northeastern Pulaski, Giles, Craig and northern Montgomery Counties in southwestern Virginia, south central Greenbrier and Monroe Counties in southeastern West Virginia and the City of Radford through 730 AM EDT

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 22 at 6:14AM EDT by NWS Indianapolis IN
properties.description:
Low temperatures will fall into the lower and middle 30s by early
Sunday morning. The presence of scattered clouds and winds at 5 to 10
mph will likely limit widespread frost development across central
Indiana...but sheltered locations may see some frost towards
daybreak. If you have sensitive plants and vegetation...be ready
to take action to protect your plants.

Additional chances for more widespread frost will come Sunday
night and perhaps Monday night in spots as well. Frost and freeze
headlines may be issued later to highlight these conditions.

NWSheadline: PATCHY FROST LATE TONIGHT AND SUNDAY MORNING

properties.description:
Relative Humidities of 25 percent or less can be expected for
4 or more hours this afternoon into the evening. Winds will be
northwest at 10 to 15 MPH.

whether you may burn outdoors.  If you do burn outside,
use extreme caution.

properties.areaDesc: Bannock, ID; Bear Lake, ID; Caribou, ID; Franklin, ID; Oneida, ID
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 21 at 3:24PM MDT by NWS Pocatello ID
properties.description:
Accelerated snowmelt is likely next week with the arrival of
warmer temperatures. Additionally, a quarter to half an inch of
rainfall is possible Monday. Small creeks and streams could
overflow along with additional ponding of lowland farmland.
Resultant flooding could impact agricultural interests along with
area roads, homes, and businesses. Increased releases on small
reservoirs are also possible, which could produce significant
rises downstream on area streams and rivers.

Clear snow, ice and debris from culverts and other flow paths to
allow runoff to flow away from buildings and other vulnerable
infrastructure. Move deep snow away from the foundations of
buildings, and move equipment and livestock out of poorly drained
or low lying areas. Remember, if you encounter a flooded roadway,
turn around don't drown, you never know what road conditions are
hidden under the water.

NWSheadline: Increased Snowmelt and Additional Flooding Possible Next Week

properties.areaDesc: Lyon, NV
properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 21 at 2:24PM PDT until April 28 at 3:00PM PDT by NWS Reno NV
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by an upstream dam release and snowmelt
continues.

* WHERE...A portion of western Nevada along the East Walker River
below Bridgeport Reservoir, including the following county, Lyon.

* WHEN...Until 300 PM PDT Friday Apr 28.

* IMPACTS...Flooding is expected to impact East Walker Road and
other low lying areas. River flows have increased and are expected
to remain elevated.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 206 PM PDT, Flooding will result in the advisory area from
an upstream dam floodgate release.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
mainly rural areas of Southern Lyon County
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

NWSheadline: FLOOD ADVISORY FOR A DAM FLOODGATE RELEASE IS NOW IN EFFECT UNTIL 3 PM PDT FRIDAY APRIL 28TH

properties.areaDesc: Burnett, WI
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 21 at 4:21PM CDT until April 24 at 10:00AM CDT by NWS Duluth MN
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt and previous rainfall continues.

* WHERE...Burnett County in northwest Wisconsin at Clam Lake and
locations downstream of the lake along the Clam River.

* WHEN...Until 1000 AM CDT Monday.

* IMPACTS...Structures along Clam Lake have been flooded over the
last week due to very elevated lake levels. Downstream flow is
elevated along the Clam River.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 414 PM CDT, emergency management reported flooding in
structures along the banks of Clam Lake. Flooding is already
occurring.
- Elevated flows are occurring along the Clam River downstream
of Clam Lake.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Siren, Webster and Saint Croix State Park.
- Flood safety information can be found at
www.weather.gov/safety/flood.
properties.instruction:
Stay away or be swept away. River banks and culverts can become
unstable and unsafe.

Report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and to the National Weather Service in Duluth when you
can do so safely. Flooding can be reported to the National Weather

properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Freeze Warning, sub-freezing temperatures as
low as 31 expected. For the Freeze Watch, sub-freezing
temperatures as low as 29 possible.

* WHERE...Portions of northwest Illinois, east central,
northeast and southeast Iowa and northeast Missouri.

* WHEN...For the Freeze Warning, from 1 AM to 9 AM CDT Saturday.
For the Freeze Watch, from late Saturday night to early Sunday
morning and late Sunday night through early Monday morning.

* IMPACTS...Frost and freeze conditions will kill crops, other
sensitive vegetation and possibly damage unprotected outdoor
plumbing.
properties.instruction:
Take steps now to protect tender plants from the cold. To prevent
freezing and possible bursting of outdoor water pipes they should
be wrapped, drained, or allowed to drip slowly. Those that have
in-ground sprinkler systems should drain them and cover above-
ground pipes to protect them from freezing.

properties.areaDesc: Maricopa, AZ
properties.headline: Air Quality Alert issued April 21 at 8:51AM MST by NWS Phoenix AZ
properties.description:
The Arizona Department of Environmental Quality (ADEQ) has extended
an Ozone High Pollution Advisory for the Phoenix Metro Area through
Saturday.

This means that forecast weather conditions combined with existing
ozone levels are expected to result in local maximum 8-hour ozone
concentrations that pose a health risk. Adverse health effects
increase as air quality deteriorates.

Ozone is an air contaminant which can cause breathing difficulties
for children, older adults, as well as persons with respiratory
problems. A decrease in physical activity is recommended.

You are urged to car pool, telecommute or use mass transit.
The use of gasoline-powered equipment should be reduced or done late
in the day.

For details on this High Pollution Advisory, visit the ADEQ internet
site at www.azdeq.gov/forecast/phoenix or call 602-771-2300.
